  "opinion": "As a mechanic who's spent decades working with engines and systems, I've always been meticulous about checking things twice. Social media's fake content can feel like a bad oil leak—it starts small, and if you don't catch it early, it can cause real problems. I don't spend much time on social media, just a few times a week, so I approach it with the same care I'd take to inspect a car. First, I verify the source. If a post claims to be from a trusted company but looks too good to be true, I cross-reference with official channels. For example, if someone posts a video claiming to be a mechanic fixing a car in under five minutes, I'd check the company's website or contact them directly. Second, I use the same critical thinking I apply to diagnosing a car issue. If something seems off, I pause and think: 'Does this make sense?' My parents both had master's degrees, so I learned early on to question assumptions and seek evidence. I also avoid sharing content that feels too sensational—I’ve seen too many times how quickly misinformation spreads. Finally, I focus on what matters: staying informed without letting it distract me. Like my hobby of cycling, I try to stay engaged but not overwhelmed. Social media can be a tool, but it's like a car—it needs regular maintenance to keep it running smoothly. If you treat it with care and skepticism, it won't become a problem.",
